1

00:00:02,030  -->  00:00:05,230
When we fit line to a set of points,

2

00:00:05,230  -->  00:00:07,610
we commonly define it by two values,

3

00:00:07,610  -->  00:00:09,795
an intercept and a slope.

4

00:00:09,795  -->  00:00:12,090
The Intercept tells us the predicted value of

5

00:00:12,090  -->  00:00:15,405
the response when the explanatory variable is zero.

6

00:00:15,405  -->  00:00:20,190
We commonly use this notation for the population and sample intercept values,

7

00:00:20,190  -->  00:00:25,770
pronounced beta knot for the parameter and B0 for the statistic.

8

00:00:25,770  -->  00:00:29,085
The slope tells us the predicted change in the response for

9

00:00:29,085  -->  00:00:33,440
each additional one unit increase in the explanatory variable.

10

00:00:33,440  -->  00:00:36,270
Similarly, the notation for the population

11

00:00:36,270  -->  00:00:39,856
and sample slope values are notated in this way,

12

00:00:39,856  -->  00:00:42,705
pronounced as beta one for the parameter,

13

00:00:42,705  -->  00:00:45,185
and B1 for the statistic.

14

00:00:45,185  -->  00:00:47,130
Once we've fit a line to these points,

15

00:00:47,130  -->  00:00:49,260
we define it with this equation.

16

00:00:49,260  -->  00:00:52,530
This point here at the beginning of the line is the intercept value,

17

00:00:52,530  -->  00:00:55,334
that is, where the x value is equal to zero.

18

00:00:55,334  -->  00:00:59,250
And if we were to increase by one along the x-axis, like this,

19

00:00:59,250  -->  00:01:03,700
then the change along the y-axis in the line is the slope value,

20

00:01:03,700  -->  00:01:06,015
one last important note on notation.

21

00:01:06,015  -->  00:01:07,740
Commonly, you will see y,

22

00:01:07,740  -->  00:01:10,425
and Y-hat values like these in regression.

23

00:01:10,425  -->  00:01:13,335
These actually notate two different things.

24

00:01:13,335  -->  00:01:17,130
Y-hat values define the values that we get from the fitted line,

25

00:01:17,130  -->  00:01:20,515
but the y defines the actual data points.

26

00:01:20,515  -->  00:01:24,255
So this value would be defined as y1, x1.

27

00:01:24,255  -->  00:01:26,000
But if we were to go to the line,

28

00:01:26,000  -->  00:01:29,100
we would define this as Y-hat_1, X1.

29

00:01:29,100  -->  00:01:31,750
Now that you understand that there are two values that

30

00:01:31,750  -->  00:01:34,230
define a line and how they're represented,

31

00:01:34,230  -->  00:01:38,040
both in notation and visually, in the next video,

32

00:01:38,040  -->  00:01:40,950
you'll see how we actually figure out what line best

33

00:01:40,950  -->  00:01:45,070
fits the points and exactly what best means.
